    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process has been a cornerstone of civil rights protection, as seen in landmark cases like Plessy v. Ferguson (1896) - although this case was later overturned, it initially legitimized segregation, but the doctrine ultimately led to Brown v. Board of Education (1954), which declared segregation unconstitutional. Additionally, it played a crucial role in Griswold v. Connecticut (1965), which established a woman's right to reproductive autonomy, and Roe v. Wade (1973), which protected a woman's right to choose. More recently, the doctrine has been used to strike down laws restricting LGBTQ+ rights, such as Lawrence v. Texas (2003).",
